In React, the `useEffect` hook is used to run side effects in a functional component. When using the `useEffect` hook, you can also specify a list of dependencies as the second argument. These dependencies determine when the effect will be re-run.

If the dependency list changes, React will run the cleanup function (if provided) for the previous effect, and then re-run the effect block again. This means that if the dependencies have changed, the effect block will be re-executed.

Here's an example to illustrate this behavior:

```jsx
import React, { useEffect, useState } from "react";

const MyComponent = () => {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  useEffect(() => {
    console.log("Effect executed!");
    return () => {
      console.log("Cleanup function executed!");
    };
  }, [count]);

  return (
    <div>
      <p>Count: {count}</p>
      <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>Increment</button>
    </div>
  );
};
```

In the above example, the effect will be executed initially when the component mounts. Then, whenever the `count` state variable changes, React will:

1. Run the cleanup function for the previous effect (if any).
2. Re-run the effect block (in this case, log "Effect executed!").
3. If subsequent changes occur, the cleanup function and the effect block will be repeated accordingly.

So, when the dependencies in `useEffect` hook change, the cleanup function will first be executed, and then the effect block will be re-run.

