Benefits of inheritance:
- Code reuse: Inheritance allows us to reuse code from the base class in the derived classes. This can save a lot of time and effort in writing new code.
- Polymorphism: Inheritance allows us to treat objects of the derived class as objects of the base class. This means that we can use objects of the derived class wherever objects of the base class are expected. This allows for more flexibility and easier maintenance of the code.

Limitations of inheritance:
- Tight coupling: If we have too many levels of inheritance, it can result in tight coupling between classes. This can make the code harder to maintain and change.
- Inherited code can become too complex: Inheriting complex code from the base class can make it difficult to understand and work with in the derived classes.

Overall, inheritance is a powerful tool in object-oriented programming that can lead to more efficient and maintainable code. However, it should be used judiciously and carefully to avoid creating overly complex and tightly coupled code.

