To organize data using arrays in C++ when sections have their own sections, you can use a multi-dimensional array or nested arrays. The data structure you choose will depend on your specific requirements and how you want to structure and access the data.

Here is an example of organizing data using nested arrays:

```cpp
#include<iostream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
   const int NUM_SECTIONS = 3;
   const int NUM_SUBSECTIONS = 4;
   const int NUM_ITEMS = 5;

   // Define a 3D array to hold the data
   int data[NUM_SECTIONS][NUM_SUBSECTIONS][NUM_ITEMS];

   // Assign values to the array elements
   for (int section = 0; section < NUM_SECTIONS; section++) {
      for (int subsection = 0; subsection < NUM_SUBSECTIONS; subsection++) {
         for (int item = 0; item < NUM_ITEMS; item++) {
            data[section][subsection][item] = section + subsection + item;
         }
      }
   }

   // Access and print the data
   for (int section = 0; section < NUM_SECTIONS; section++) {
      cout << "Section " << section << ":" << endl;
      for (int subsection = 0; subsection < NUM_SUBSECTIONS; subsection++) {
         cout << "  Subsection " << subsection << ": ";
         for (int item = 0; item < NUM_ITEMS; item++) {
            cout << data[section][subsection][item] << " ";
         }
         cout << endl;
      }
      cout << endl;
   }

   return 0;
}
```

In this example, the data array is defined as a 3-dimensional array with dimensions for sections, subsections, and items. You can change the values of `NUM_SECTIONS`, `NUM_SUBSECTIONS`, and `NUM_ITEMS` to match your specific requirements.

The data is assigned values using nested loops, and then accessed and printed using similar nested loops to traverse the array.

Remember to adjust the size and structure of the array based on your specific needs.
